For the Hak5 Shark Jack, the most practical way to do this is with a Bash payload, since the Shark Jack runs OpenWrt Linux and its payload system (payload.sh) executes Bash scripts. You can test a port using netcat (nc) and then control the device LEDs using the built-in LED command.

Below is a clean, reliable payload that:

Tests a specific port on a target IP

Turns GREEN LED if the port is OPEN

Turns RED LED if the port is CLOSED

Provides a quick timeout so the scan does not hang

Shark Jack Payload – Port Open/Closed Test

Create a file named:

payload.sh
#!/bin/bash

# Target settings
TARGET="192.168.1.1"
PORT="22"
TIMEOUT=2

# Start indicator
LED SETUP
LED ATTACK

# Test the port using netcat
nc -z -w $TIMEOUT $TARGET $PORT

# Check result
if [ $? -eq 0 ]; then
    # Port is OPEN
    LED GREEN
else
    # Port is CLOSED
    LED RED
fi
How It Works
Port Test
nc -z -w 2 TARGET PORT

-z → scan mode (no data sent)

-w → timeout

exit code 0 = open

exit code 1 = closed

LED Control

Shark Jack supports:

LED SETUP
LED ATTACK
LED GREEN
LED RED
LED OFF

So we simply check the exit code:

if [ $? -eq 0 ]
Example Use Case

Testing if SSH is open on a gateway

TARGET="192.168.1.1"
PORT="22"

